\b a. What is Test Driven Development (TDD)?\b0\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b Test-Driven Development \b0 (\b TDD\b0 ) is a software development technique that relates to the concept of verification and validation and is based on a short cycle of repetitions.\par
First the \b developer writes an automated test case\b0  that \b defines a required improvement \b0 or new functionality. \par
\b Create precise test / Correcting the Code / Refactor the Code\par
\b0 (TDD)\b  is a software development practice that focuses on creating unit test cases before developing the actual code\b0 . It is an iterative approach combining programming, unit test creation, and refactoring.\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b b.Test Driven Development (TDD) Examples\b0\par
Calculator Function: When building a calculator function, a TDD approach would involve writing a test case for the \ldblquote add\rdblquote  function and then writing the code for the process to pass that test. Once the \ldblquote add\rdblquote  function is working correctly, additional test cases would be written for other functions such as \ldblquote subtract\rdblquote , \ldblquote multiply\rdblquote  and \ldblquote divide\rdblquote .\par
User Authentication: When building a user authentication system, a TDD approach would involve writing a test case for the user login functionality and then writing the code for the login process to pass that test. Once the login functionality works correctly, additional test cases will be written for registration, password reset, and account verification.\par
\par
\b c. Three Phases of Test Driven Development\b0\par
Create precise tests: Developers need to create exact unit tests to verify the functionality of specific features. They must ensure that the test compiles so that it can execute. In most cases, the test is bound to fail. This is a meaningful failure as developers create compact tests based on their assumptions of how the feature will behave.\par
Correcting the Code: Once a test fails, developers must make the minimal changes required to update the code to run successfully when re-executed.\par
Refactor the Code: Once the test runs successfully, check for redundancy or any possible code optimizations to enhance overall performance. Ensure that refactoring does not affect the external behavior of the program.\par
